          <button class="faq-button w-full px-6 py-5 text-left font-bold text-primary flex items-center justify-between focus:outline-none">
            <span>What is the minimum civil work required for a home lift?</span>
            <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="faq-icon w-5 h-5 transition-transform"></i>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer hidden px-6 pb-5 text-slate-600 text-sm border-t border-slate-100 pt-4 leading-relaxed">
            For modern home lifts, specifically Machine Room-Less (MRL) and hydraulic lifts, minimal civil work is needed. In many cases, we do not require a deep pit (only 150mm to 300mm is sufficient) or an overhead machine room. They can be installed inside a self-supporting steel structure alongside your staircase.
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- FAQ 2 -->
        <div class="faq-item bg-white border border-slate-200 rounded-xl overflow-hidden shadow-sm">
          <button class="faq-button w-full px-6 py-5 text-left font-bold text-primary flex items-center justify-between focus:outline-none">
            <span>How does the Auto Rescue Device (ARD) operate during a power failure?</span>
            <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="faq-icon w-5 h-5 transition-transform"></i>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer hidden px-6 pb-5 text-slate-600 text-sm border-t border-slate-100 pt-4 leading-relaxed">
            An Auto Rescue Device (ARD) is a critical safety system. If utility power goes out while the lift is running, the ARD automatically switches on using an emergency battery pack. It runs the elevator cabin slowly to the nearest landing floor, opens the automatic doors, and safely evacuates the passengers before turning off.
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- FAQ 3 -->
        <div class="faq-item bg-white border border-slate-200 rounded-xl overflow-hidden shadow-sm">
          <button class="faq-button w-full px-6 py-5 text-left font-bold text-primary flex items-center justify-between focus:outline-none">
            <span>What are the standard packages for AMC (Annual Maintenance)?</span>
            <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="faq-icon w-5 h-5 transition-transform"></i>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer hidden px-6 pb-5 text-slate-600 text-sm border-t border-slate-100 pt-4 leading-relaxed">
            We offer two main packages:
            <ul class="list-disc list-inside mt-2 space-y-1">
              <li><strong>Semi-Comprehensive AMC:</strong> Includes monthly maintenance checks, oil and grease servicing, and emergency breakdown support. Parts are charged extra.</li>
              <li><strong>Comprehensive AMC:</strong> Covers monthly servicing, breakdown calls, plus all major mechanical and electronic parts (like control cards, motors, ropes, and locks) replaced free of charge.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- FAQ 4 -->
        <div class="faq-item bg-white border border-slate-200 rounded-xl overflow-hidden shadow-sm">
          <button class="faq-button w-full px-6 py-5 text-left font-bold text-primary flex items-center justify-between focus:outline-none">
            <span>Can a residential elevator run on standard household single-phase electricity?</span>
            <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="faq-icon w-5 h-5 transition-transform"></i>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer hidden px-6 pb-5 text-slate-600 text-sm border-t border-slate-100 pt-4 leading-relaxed">
            Yes! Our home lifts are engineered with high-efficiency gearless permanent magnet synchronous motors (PMSM) or hydraulic power packs that can operate on standard 220V single-phase domestic power supply. They require very little energy, similar to a 1.5-ton household air conditioner.
